The Living Marketplace: A Guide to Dynamic Commerce
Commerce is the lifeblood of Skyrim, and this system makes it a dynamic and integral part of the adventure. It is designed as a fast-paced, engaging activity for the entire table, turning every visit to a merchant into an opportunity for discovery and memorable roleplaying. This framework rewards player exploration and clever interaction, ensuring the world's economy feels as alive and responsive as its people.
The system is built on two pillars: What They Have (Dynamic Inventory) and How You Buy It (The Merchant's Preference).
Pillar 1: What They Have (The Dynamic Inventory)
Every merchant's inventory is divided into two distinct categories, ensuring a balance between reliability and the thrill of discovery.
Standard Stock: This is the predictable inventory a merchant always has. It consists of common, essential items appropriate to their profession and location. This ensures players can always acquire basic necessities like potions, arrows, or common crafting materials.
Special Stock (Rotating): This is a limited, randomized selection of rare, magical, unique, or exceptionally well-made items. This inventory represents new shipments, a master artisan's latest creation, or a lucky find. It rotates after a long in-game period (e.g., a month) or after a major world event, giving players a powerful reason to revisit towns and check in with merchants.
The Merchant Tier System
Merchants are categorized into tiers based on their location's size and wealth. This determines the quality of their Standard Stock and the number of "slots" they have for valuable Special Stock.
